41    final class ControlFlowAnalysis implements Callback, CompilerPass {
42   
43    /**
44    * Based roughly on the first few pages of
45    *
46    * "Declarative Intraprocedural Flow Analysis of Java Source Code by
47    * Nilsson-Nyman, Hedin, Magnusson & Ekman",
48    *
49    * this pass computes the control flow graph from the AST. However, a full
50    * attribute grammar is not necessary. We will compute the flow edges with a
51    * single post order traversal. The "follow()" of a given node will be
52    * computed recursively in a demand driven fashion.
53    *
54    * As of this moment, we are not performing any inter-procedural analysis
55    * within our framework.
56    */
57

90    /*
91    * This stack captures the structure of nested TRY blocks. The top of the
92    * stack is the inner most TRY block. A FUNCTION node in this stack implies
93    * that the handler is determined by the caller of the function at runtime.
94    */
95    private final Deque<Node> exceptionHandler = new ArrayDeque<Node>();
96   
97    /*
98    * This map is used to handle the follow of FINALLY. For example:
99    *
100    * while(x) {
101    * try {
102    * try {
103    * break;
104    * } catch (a) {
105    * } finally {
106    * foo();
107    * }
108    * fooFollow();
109    * } catch (b) {
110    * } finally {
111    * bar();
112    * }
113    * barFollow();
114    * }
115    * END();
116    *
117    * In this case finallyMap will contain a map from:
118    * first FINALLY -> bar()
119    * second FINALLY -> END()
120    *
121    * When we are connecting foo() and bar() to to their respective follow, we
122    * must also look up this map and connect:
123    * foo() -> bar()
124    * bar() -> END
125    */
126    private final Multimap<Node, Node> finallyMap = HashMultimap.create();
